{"title_page": "Miller Brittain", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Miller Brittain\n| image         = Miller_Brittain_self.jpg \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Miller Gore Brittain\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1912|11|12}}\n| birth_place   = [[Saint John, New Brunswick]], Canada\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1968|01|21|1912|11|12}}\n| death_place   = Saint John, New Brunswick, Canada\n| nationality   = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| field         = [[Painting]]\n| training      = Saint John Vocational School, Arts Students League of New York\n| movement      = [[Social realism]], [[Irony]]\n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| influenced by =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        = Canadian Centennial Medal\n}}\n'''Miller Gore Brittain''' (November 12, 1912 &ndash; January 21, 1968) was a [[Canadian]] artist from [[Saint John, New Brunswick]].<ref name=\"cyber\">{{cite web |url=http://cybermuse.gallery.ca/cybermuse/search/bio_e.jsp?iartistid=728 |title=Miller Brittain - Biography |publisher=[[National Gallery of Canada]] |accessdate=2009-10-25 }}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nHe was born and raised in [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]]. Brittain studied art with Elizabeth Russell Holt in Saint John and [[Harry Wickey]] in [[New York City]]. In 1932, after living in New York, he returned to Saint John, where he worked at clerical and construction jobs and opened an art studio on the waterfront. During this period, he captured realistic scenes of everyday life in the city which incorporated social commentary. Brittain served with the [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] during [[World War II]] and served two years as a war artist.\n\nBrittain was a founding member of the [[Federation of Canadian Artists]] in 1941. After the war, his paintings took on a more surreal aspect, taking as their subject biblical topics,<ref name=\"cyber\"/> abstract figures, nudes and flowers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mcmichael.com/exhibitions/millerbrittain/indexpast.cfm |title=Miller Brittain: When the Stars Threw Down Their Spears |publisher=[[McMichael Canadian Art Collection]] |year=2008 |accessdate=2009-10-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090705221203/http://www.mcmichael.com/exhibitions/millerbrittain/indexpast.cfm |archive-date=July 5, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Brittain had married Connie Starr in 1951; he was devastated by her death from cancer seven years later and was treated several times for [[alcoholism]] in his later life.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gallery.ca/brittain/en/20.htm |title=About Miller Brittain |publisher=[[National Gallery of Canada]] |year=2009 |accessdate=2009-10-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091111155723/http://www.gallery.ca/brittain/en/20.htm |archive-date=November 11, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBrittain is considered one of Canada's most prolific painters. His work broke from contemporary style at the time of the Group of Seven when landscapes of the country dominated Canada's art scene. Brittain focused on working class life in his hometown of Saint John with his signature style in social-realism.\n\nThe [[National Film Board of Canada]] produced a film based on his life in 1981. The film was awarded Best Overall Entry at the [[Atlantic Film Festival]] in 1982.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.onf-nfb.gc.ca/eng/collection/film/?id=13590 |title=Miller Brittain |publisher=National Film Board of Canada |accessdate=2009-10-25}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Saint John, New Brunswick street scape, Princess St..jpg|thumb|Princess St. in uptown Saint John near Brittain's studio.]]\n\nBrittain's work is held in private collections and a number of art galleries in Canada including the [[Beaverbrook Art Gallery]], the [[National Gallery of Canada]] and the [[Canadian War Museum]] and retrospectives of his work have appeared in various Canadian galleries including the [[McMichael Canadian Art Collection]] and the [[National Gallery of Canada]].\n\n==Life in Saint John==\nAfter studying in New York, Brittain felt he didn't have to leave the region to make a career as an artist. However, at the time [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]] was still recovering from three major fires and was in the middle of the Depression. As a young man he worked as a draftsman and worked on the docks while working on his craft amongst a thriving arts community including Ruth Starr, Ted Campbell, Fred Ross and [[Jack Humphrey]]. In January 1949, his first major exhibit at the [[New Brunswick Museum]] in Saint John. The exhibition was so popular he went on to do a series of solo shows in New York. In 1968, Brittain was awarded the Canadian Centennial Medal for his contribution to Canadian art.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://w3.stu.ca/stu/sites/nble/b/brittain_miller.html|accessdate=2 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nIn 1968, he died tragically of a stroke at the age of 55 after years of struggling with alcoholism. Brittain was an icon of the Saint John arts community and presence is still felt in the city's arts scene today. The popular Britt's Pub, named for the artist, is on the ground floor of his studio at 42 Princess St.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Canadian official war artists]]\n* [[War artist]]\n* [[Military art]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0227057}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brittain, Miller}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian male painters]]\n[[Category:Artists from Saint John, New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Canadian war artists]]\n[[Category:World War II artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Miller Brittain\n| image         = Miller_Brittain_self.jpg \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Miller Gore Brittain\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1912|11|12}}\n| birth_place   = [[Saint John, New Brunswick]], Canada\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1968|01|21|1912|11|12}}\n| death_place   = Saint John, New Brunswick, Canada\n| nationality   = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| field         = [[Painting]]\n| training      = Saint John Vocational School, Arts Students League of New York\n| movement      = [[Social realism]], [[Irony]]\n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| influenced by =\n| influenced    =\n| awards        = Canadian Centennial Medal\n}}\n'''Miller Gore Brittain''' (November 12, 1912 &ndash; January 21, 1968) was a [[Canadian]] artist from [[New Brunswick]].<ref name=\"cyber\">{{cite web |url=http://cybermuse.gallery.ca/cybermuse/search/bio_e.jsp?iartistid=728 |title=Miller Brittain - Biography |publisher=[[National Gallery of Canada]] |accessdate=2009-10-25 }}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nHe was born in [[Saint John, New Brunswick]]. Brittain studied art with Elizabeth Russell Holt in Saint John and [[Harry Wickey]] in [[New York City]]. In 1932, he returned to Saint John, where he worked at clerical and construction jobs and opened an art studio on the waterfront. During this period, he captured realistic scenes of everyday life in the city which incorporated social commentary. Brittain served with the [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] during [[World War II]] and served two years as a war artist.\n\nBrittain was a founding member of the [[Federation of Canadian Artists]] in 1941. After the war, his paintings took on a more surreal aspect, taking as their subject biblical topics,<ref name=\"cyber\"/> abstract figures, nudes and flowers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mcmichael.com/exhibitions/millerbrittain/indexpast.cfm |title=Miller Brittain: When the Stars Threw Down Their Spears |publisher=[[McMichael Canadian Art Collection]] |year=2008 |accessdate=2009-10-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090705221203/http://www.mcmichael.com/exhibitions/millerbrittain/indexpast.cfm |archive-date=July 5, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Brittain had married Connie Starr in 1951; he was devastated by her death from cancer seven years later and was treated several times for [[alcoholism]] in his later life.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gallery.ca/brittain/en/20.htm |title=About Miller Brittain |publisher=[[National Gallery of Canada]] |year=2009 |accessdate=2009-10-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091111155723/http://www.gallery.ca/brittain/en/20.htm |archive-date=November 11, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBrittain is considered one of Canada's most prolific painters. His work broke from contemporary style at the time of the Group of Seven when landscapes of the country dominated Canada's art scene. Brittain focused on working class life in his hometown of Saint John with his signature style in social-realism.\n\nThe [[National Film Board of Canada]] produced a film based on his life in 1981. The film was awarded Best Overall Entry at the [[Atlantic Film Festival]] in 1982.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.onf-nfb.gc.ca/eng/collection/film/?id=13590 |title=Miller Brittain |publisher=National Film Board of Canada |accessdate=2009-10-25}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Saint John, New Brunswick street scape, Princess St..jpg|thumb|Princess St. in uptown Saint John near Brittain's studio.]]\n\nBrittain's work is held in private collections and a number of art galleries in Canada including the [[Beaverbrook Art Gallery]], the [[National Gallery of Canada]] and the [[Canadian War Museum]] and retrospectives of his work have appeared in various Canadian galleries including the [[McMichael Canadian Art Collection]] and the [[National Gallery of Canada]].\n\n==Life in Saint John==\nAfter studying in New York, Brittain felt he didn't have to leave the region to make a career as an artist. However, at the time [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]] was still recovering from three major fires and was in the middle of the Depression. As a young man he worked as a draftsman and worked on the docks while working on his craft amongst a thriving arts community including Ruth Starr, Ted Campbell, Fred Ross and [[Jack Humphrey]]. In January 1949, his first major exhibit at the [[New Brunswick Museum]] in Saint John. The exhibition was so popular he went on to do a series of solo shows in New York. In 1968, Brittain was awarded the Canadian Centennial Medal for his contribution to Canadian art.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://w3.stu.ca/stu/sites/nble/b/brittain_miller.html|accessdate=2 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nIn 1968, he died tragically of a stroke at the age of 55 after years of struggling with alcoholism. Brittain was an icon of the Saint John arts community and presence is still felt in the city's arts scene today. The popular Britt's Pub, named for the artist, is on the ground floor of his studio at 42 Princess St.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Canadian official war artists]]\n* [[War artist]]\n* [[Military art]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0227057}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brittain, Miller}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian painters]]\n[[Category:Canadian male painters]]\n[[Category:Artists from Saint John, New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Canadian war artists]]\n[[Category:World War II artists]]\n", "name_user": "Johnserss12", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miller_Brittain"}
{"title_page": "Leader of the Opposition (Northern Territory)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\nThe '''Leader of the Opposition''' is an official role usually occupied by the leader of the second largest party in the [[Northern Territory Legislative Assembly]]. In the event that that party or coalition wins an election, the Leader of the Opposition will most likely become the [[Chief Minister of the Northern Territory|Chief Minister]].<ref>[http://www.nt.gov.au/lant/Parliaison/2010%20June%20Newsletter.pdf Schools Newsletter], Parliamentary Relations and Education Unit (Legislative Assembly of the Northern Territory), June 2010.</ref>\n\nWhile the Legislative Assembly was created in 1974, there was no parliamentary opposition for the first three-year term, as every seat was held by the government, with the exception of two that were won by independents.\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border:1px solid #aaa; border-collapse:collapse\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#cccccc\"\n! '''#'''\n! '''Opposition Leader'''<ref>[http://www.nt.gov.au/lant/pub/OFFICE%20HOLDERS%201ST-11TH.pdf Office Holders 1st\u201311th Assemblies], [[Government of the Northern Territory]], 9 February 2009.</ref>\n! colspan=2|'''Party'''\n! '''Dates in Opposition'''\n|-\n| 1\n| [[Jon Isaacs]]\n{{Party name with colour|Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)}}\n| 21 September 1977 \u2013 1 November 1981\n|- \n| 2\n| [[Bob Collins (Australian politician)|Bob Collins]]\n{{Party name with colour|Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)}}\n| 2 November 1981 \u2013 18 August 1986\n|- \n| 3\n| [[Terry Smith (politician)|Terry Smith]]\n{{Party name with colour|Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)}}\n| 19 August 1986 \u2013 1 November 1990\n|- \n| 4\n| [[Brian Ede]]\n{{Party name with colour|Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)}}\n| 2 November 1990 \u2013 9 April 1996\n|- \n| 5\n| [[Maggie Hickey]]\n{{Party name with colour|Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)}}\n| 16 April 1996 \u2013 2 February 1999\n|- \n| 6\n| [[Clare Martin]]\n{{Party name with colour|Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)}}\n| 3 February 1999 \u2013 26 August 2001\n|- \n| 7\n| [[Denis Burke (Australian politician)|Denis Burke]]\n{{Party name with colour|Country Liberal Party}}\n| 28 August 2001 \u2013 14 November 2003\n|- \n| 8\n| [[Terry Mills (Australian politician)|Terry Mills]]\n{{Party name with colour|Country Liberal Party}}\n| 15 November 2003 \u2013 4 February 2005\n|- \n| (7)\n| [[Denis Burke (Australian politician)|Denis Burke]]\n{{Party name with colour|Country Liberal Party}}\n| 7 February 2005 \u2013 17 June 2005\n|- \n| 9\n| [[Jodeen Carney]]\n{{Party name with colour|Country Liberal Party}}\n| 29 June 2005 \u2013 28 January 2008\n|- \n| (8)\n| [[Terry Mills (Australian politician)|Terry Mills]]\n{{Party name with colour|Country Liberal Party}}\n| 29 January 2008 \u2013 29 August 2012\n|- \n| 10\n| [[Delia Lawrie]]\n{{Party name with colour|Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)}}\n| 29 August 2012 \u2013 20 April 2015\n|- \n| 11\n| [[Michael Gunner]]\n{{Party name with colour|Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)}}\n| 20 April 2015 \u2013 31 August 2016\n|- \n| 12\n| [[Gary Higgins]]\n{{Party name with colour|Country Liberal Party}}\n| 2 September 2016 \u2013 1 February 2020\n|- \n| 13\n| [[Lia Finocchiaro]]\n{{Party name with colour|Country Liberal Party}}\n| 1 February 2020 \u2013 18 March 2020\n|-\n|(8)\n|Terry Mills\n{{Party name with colour|Territory Alliance}}\n|18 March 2020 - Present\n|- \n|}\n\n==2020 Opposition Leadership dispute==\n\nOn 18 March 2020 [[Terry Mills (Australian politician)|Terry Mills]] claimed to have become Opposition Leader on the basis of the [[Territory Alliance]] now having three MLAs to the [[Country_Liberal_Party|Country Liberal Party's]] two.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.ntnews.com.au/news/northern-territory/robyn-lambley-joins-terry-mills-territory-alliance-sets-up-almighty-clp-showdown/news-story/b1a09c5f1a7595e96d222b9357b1435e|title = Territory Alliance says it has taken NT Opposition status|accessdate = 24 Mar 2020}}</ref>  No motion acknowledging a change in the office was passed by the Assembly.  On 24 March 2020 Mills presented a shadow Cabinet to the Assembly and was initially referred to as Leader of the Opposition, without formal motion.  However later that day [[Lia Finocchiaro]] moved that the office of Leader of the Opposition be declared vacant as it was \"unclear\" who the \"official opposition\" was, and that a secret ballot between the two be held to determine Opposition Leader status.  The motion was passed and Finocchiaro won the ballot 5-3<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.territorystories.nt.gov.au/jspui/bitstream/10070/756617/5/Draft%20Daily%20Hansard%20-%20Tuesday%2024%20March%202020   |title = Draft Daily Hansard 24 March 2020 |accessdate = 24 Mar 2020}}</ref>, with Labor MLAs present not voting. <ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.ntnews.com.au/news/northern-territory/clp-returned-as-nt-opposition-in-shock-ballot/news-story/1988ca7d6053697d7ceda139076ff623|title = CLP returned as NT Opposition in shock ballot|accessdate = 24 Mar 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Government of the Northern Territory}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leader Of The Opposition (Northern Territory)}}\n[[Category:Lists of Leaders of the Opposition of Australian states and territories|Northern Territory]]\n[[Category:Members of the Northern Territory Legislative Assembly| ]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Opposition in the Northern Territory| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}\nThe '''Leader of the Opposition''' is an official role usually occupied by the leader of the second largest party in the [[Northern Territory Legislative Assembly]]. In the event that that party or coalition wins an election, the Leader of the Opposition will most likely become the [[Chief Minister of the Northern Territory|Chief Minister]].<ref>[http://www.nt.gov.au/lant/Parliaison/2010%20June%20Newsletter.pdf Schools Newsletter], Parliamentary Relations and Education Unit (Legislative Assembly of the Northern Territory), June 2010.</ref>\n\nWhile the Legislative Assembly was created in 1974, there was no parliamentary opposition for the first three-year term, as every seat was held by the government, with the exception of two that were won by independents.\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border:1px solid #aaa; border-collapse:collapse\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#cccccc\"\n! '''#'''\n! '''Opposition Leader'''<ref>[http://www.nt.gov.au/lant/pub/OFFICE%20HOLDERS%201ST-11TH.pdf Office Holders 1st\u201311th Assemblies], [[Government of the Northern Territory]], 9 February 2009.</ref>\n! colspan=2|'''Party'''\n! '''Dates in Opposition'''\n|-\n| 1\n| [[Jon Isaacs]]\n{{Party name with colour|Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)}}\n| 21 September 1977 \u2013 1 November 1981\n|- \n| 2\n| [[Bob Collins (Australian politician)|Bob Collins]]\n{{Party name with colour|Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)}}\n| 2 November 1981 \u2013 18 August 1986\n|- \n| 3\n| [[Terry Smith (politician)|Terry Smith]]\n{{Party name with colour|Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)}}\n| 19 August 1986 \u2013 1 November 1990\n|- \n| 4\n| [[Brian Ede]]\n{{Party name with colour|Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)}}\n| 2 November 1990 \u2013 9 April 1996\n|- \n| 5\n| [[Maggie Hickey]]\n{{Party name with colour|Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)}}\n| 16 April 1996 \u2013 2 February 1999\n|- \n| 6\n| [[Clare Martin]]\n{{Party name with colour|Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)}}\n| 3 February 1999 \u2013 26 August 2001\n|- \n| 7\n| [[Denis Burke (Australian politician)|Denis Burke]]\n{{Party name with colour|Country Liberal Party}}\n| 28 August 2001 \u2013 14 November 2003\n|- \n| 8\n| [[Terry Mills (Australian politician)|Terry Mills]]\n{{Party name with colour|Country Liberal Party}}\n| 15 November 2003 \u2013 4 February 2005\n|- \n| (7)\n| [[Denis Burke (Australian politician)|Denis Burke]]\n{{Party name with colour|Country Liberal Party}}\n| 7 February 2005 \u2013 17 June 2005\n|- \n| 9\n| [[Jodeen Carney]]\n{{Party name with colour|Country Liberal Party}}\n| 29 June 2005 \u2013 28 January 2008\n|- \n| (8)\n| [[Terry Mills (Australian politician)|Terry Mills]]\n{{Party name with colour|Country Liberal Party}}\n| 29 January 2008 \u2013 29 August 2012\n|- \n| 10\n| [[Delia Lawrie]]\n{{Party name with colour|Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)}}\n| 29 August 2012 \u2013 20 April 2015\n|- \n| 11\n| [[Michael Gunner]]\n{{Party name with colour|Australian Labor Party (Northern Territory Branch)}}\n| 20 April 2015 \u2013 31 August 2016\n|- \n| 12\n| [[Gary Higgins]]\n{{Party name with colour|Country Liberal Party}}\n| 2 September 2016 \u2013 1 February 2020\n|- \n| 13\n| [[Lia Finocchiaro]]\n{{Party name with colour|Country Liberal Party}}\n| 1 February 2020 \u2013 18 March 2020\n|-\n|(8)\n|Terry Mills\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align: left;\" scope=\"row\" |\n|Territory Alliance\n|18 March 2020 - Present\n|- \n|}\n\n==2020 Opposition Leadership dispute==\n\nOn 18 March 2020 [[Terry Mills (Australian politician)|Terry Mills]] claimed to have become Opposition Leader on the basis of the [[Territory Alliance]] now having three MLAs to the [[Country_Liberal_Party|Country Liberal Party's]] two.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.ntnews.com.au/news/northern-territory/robyn-lambley-joins-terry-mills-territory-alliance-sets-up-almighty-clp-showdown/news-story/b1a09c5f1a7595e96d222b9357b1435e|title = Territory Alliance says it has taken NT Opposition status|accessdate = 24 Mar 2020}}</ref>  No motion acknowledging a change in the office was passed by the Assembly.  On 24 March 2020 Mills presented a shadow Cabinet to the Assembly and was initially referred to as Leader of the Opposition, without formal motion.  However later that day [[Lia Finocchiaro]] moved that the office of Leader of the Opposition be declared vacant as it was \"unclear\" who the \"official opposition\" was, and that a secret ballot between the two be held to determine Opposition Leader status.  The motion was passed and Finocchiaro won the ballot 5-3<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.territorystories.nt.gov.au/jspui/bitstream/10070/756617/5/Draft%20Daily%20Hansard%20-%20Tuesday%2024%20March%202020   |title = Draft Daily Hansard 24 March 2020 |accessdate = 24 Mar 2020}}</ref>, with Labor MLAs present not voting. <ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.ntnews.com.au/news/northern-territory/clp-returned-as-nt-opposition-in-shock-ballot/news-story/1988ca7d6053697d7ceda139076ff623|title = CLP returned as NT Opposition in shock ballot|accessdate = 24 Mar 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Government of the Northern Territory}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leader Of The Opposition (Northern Territory)}}\n[[Category:Lists of Leaders of the Opposition of Australian states and territories|Northern Territory]]\n[[Category:Members of the Northern Territory Legislative Assembly| ]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Opposition in the Northern Territory| ]]\n", "name_user": "YttriumShrew", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leader_of_the_Opposition_(Northern_Territory)"}
{"title_page": "Lyubka Rondova", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n|name         = Lyubka Rondova\n|image        = Lubka-Rondova.jpg\n|background   = solo_singer\n|birth_name   =\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1936|9|24|mf=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[Sidirochori]], [[Greece]]\n|death_date   = {{Death date and age|2016|03|15|1936|09|24|mf=y}}\n|death_place  = [[Sofia]], [[Bulgaria]]\n|genre        = [[Folk music|Folk]]\n|years_active =\n}}\n\n'''Lyubka Vasileva Rondova''' ({{lang-bg|\u041b\u044e\u0431\u043a\u0430 \u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u043d\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430}}), '''Ljubka Rondova''' or '''Lubka Rondova''' was a [[Bulgarians|Bulgarian]] [[folk singer]] best known for performing and recording many of the traditional songs from [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]] as a folklore region.\n\nRondova was born in Sidirochori ([[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]]: \u0428\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043e\u0432\u043e, Shesteovo), [[Vitsi]] municipality, [[Kastoria Prefecture]], [[Greece]] in 1936. In 1948, at the end of the [[Greek Civil War]], she left her village and went to [[Poland]] with many [[Political refugees of the Greek Civil War|children-refugees]] from the western part of [[Greek Macedonia]]. Later she moved to [[Czechoslovakia]] and graduated  in [[Slavistics]] from [[Charles University in Prague]]. Rondova and her family settled in [[Bulgaria]] in 1960.\n\nRondova was invited to join the song and dance ensemble \"Gotse Delchev\" in [[Sofia]] and was its soloist 30 years.\n\nShe was awarded the highest Bulgarian [[Order (decoration)|order]] Stara planina, First Degree in 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.daxy.com/dvz/2002_eng/054.html|title=Official Gazette|date=May 31, 2002|newspaper=Daxy|issue=54|url-access=subscription}}</ref> She died on March 15, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bgnes.com/laifstail/kultura/4415737/|title=\u041f\u043e\u0447\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u041b\u044e\u0431\u043a\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u043d\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430|trans-title=The folk singer Lyubka Rondova passed away|work=BGNES|date=March 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* {{YouTube|0wZXnsDIcpE|A folk song \"Veliko, diulber Bugarko\"}}\n* [http://www.vbox7.com/play:880f8ce4 A folk song \"Black death appeared\"] at [[Vbox7]]\n* {{YouTube|8OV9_HZD2SI|A folk song \"Momi Tikveshanki\"}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rondova, Lyubka}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kastoria]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian folk singers]]\n[[Category:Bulgarians from Aegean Macedonia]]\n[[Category:Charles University in Prague alumni]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian female singers]]\n[[Category:Macedonian Bulgarians]]\n[[Category:Child refugees]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian-language singers]]\n\n\n{{Bulgaria-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n|name         = Lyubka Rondova\n|image        = Lubka-Rondova.jpg\n|background   = solo_singer\n|birth_name   =\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1936|9|24|mf=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[Sidirochori]], [[Greece]]\n|death_date   = {{Death date and age|2016|03|15|1936|09|24|mf=y}}\n|death_place  = [[Sofia]], [[Bulgaria]]\n|genre        = [[Folk music|Folk]]\n|years_active =\n}}\n\n'''Lyubka Vasileva Rondova''' ({{lang-bg|\u041b\u044e\u0431\u043a\u0430 \u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u043d\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430}}), '''Ljubka Rondova''' or '''Lubka Rondova''' ({{lang-bg|\u041b\u044e\u0431\u043a\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u043d\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430}}) was a [[Bulgarians|Bulgarian]] [[folk singer]] best known for performing and recording many of the traditional songs from [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]] as a folklore region.\n\nRondova was born in Sidirochori ([[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]]: \u0428\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043e\u0432\u043e, Shesteovo), [[Vitsi]] municipality, [[Kastoria Prefecture]], [[Greece]] in 1936. In 1948, at the end of the [[Greek Civil War]], she left her village and went to [[Poland]] with many [[Political refugees of the Greek Civil War|children-refugees]] from the western part of [[Greek Macedonia]]. Later she moved to [[Czechoslovakia]] and graduated  in [[Slavistics]] from [[Charles University in Prague]]. Rondova and her family settled in [[Bulgaria]] in 1960.\n\nRondova was invited to join the song and dance ensemble \"Gotse Delchev\" in [[Sofia]] and was its soloist 30 years.\n\nShe was awarded the highest Bulgarian [[Order (decoration)|order]] Stara planina, First Degree in 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.daxy.com/dvz/2002_eng/054.html|title=Official Gazette|date=May 31, 2002|newspaper=Daxy|issue=54|url-access=subscription}}</ref> She died on March 15, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bgnes.com/laifstail/kultura/4415737/|title=\u041f\u043e\u0447\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u041b\u044e\u0431\u043a\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u043d\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430|trans-title=The folk singer Lyubka Rondova passed away|work=BGNES|date=March 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* {{YouTube|0wZXnsDIcpE|A folk song \"Veliko, diulber Bugarko\"}}\n* [http://www.vbox7.com/play:880f8ce4 A folk song \"Black death appeared\"] at [[Vbox7]]\n* {{YouTube|8OV9_HZD2SI|A folk song \"Momi Tikveshanki\"}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rondova, Lyubka}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kastoria]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian folk singers]]\n[[Category:Bulgarians from Aegean Macedonia]]\n[[Category:Charles University in Prague alumni]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian female singers]]\n[[Category:Macedonian Bulgarians]]\n[[Category:Child refugees]]\n[[Category:Bulgarian-language singers]]\n\n\n{{Bulgaria-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "StanProg", "label": "safe", "comment": "unnecessary duplication", "